On this day in history in 1886, Apache leader Geronimo surrendered to U.S. troops, marking the end of the Indian Wars in the Southwest. 

Born in present-day Arizona and Mexico, Geronimo grew up amid conflict with settlers encroaching on his tribe's land. After his family was killed by Mexicans, he led raids against both Mexican and American settlers in revenge. After 30 years of fighting to protect his tribe‚Äôs land, Geronimo surrendered, making him the last major Native American warrior to do so.

Geronimo was relocated to Florida, then Alabama, and finally to a reservation in Oklahoma Territory, where he adapted to a new life as a farmer and converted to Christianity. He participated in President Theodore Roosevelt‚Äôs inaugural parade and died at Fort Sill in 1909.

text:
I wanted to share some additional information with you regarding the Epstein witness statements to members of Congress. This material is not classified and relates to what has now become a very large congressional investigation:

*In my opinion, there is definitely an intelligence connection. Countries named by the lead attorney for the witnesses included Saudi Arabia, Russia, and Israel, as well as a former CIA director (inferred to be the CIA director under the Bush administration, based on the attorney‚Äôs description of interactions while Epstein was in his work/arrest program).

*The 30,000+ files are in the process of being loaded into a more accessible and searchable format. These files include the Ghislaine Maxwell transcript and audio, full videos of Epstein‚Äôs cell (including the missing minute), as well as courthouse documents that had to be formally requested, as they were not easily accessible. There are also thousands of pages of records, including DOJ emails.

*The witnesses have stated they were unable to obtain their own files, and we are actively working to provide those to them. Again, previous admins denied them. But the Trump admin is assisting. Big difference. 

*The SARS report, which will eventually be made public, will include names.

*There is an active class action lawsuit involving the victims and the bank. Therefore, we must be careful to ensure this investigation is not used to influence the lawsuit, in accordance with ethical standards.

This is a very large and expansive investigation. To be clear, the end goal is not only to deliver justice for the victims but also, equally important, to make criminal referrals to the DOJ.

It is also important to understand how frightening this is for some of the women involved. In some cases, they were threatened. With that in mind, I will continue to provide updates on what we can share without jeopardizing the investigation. I also want to emphasize that both the victims and others have stated to the press that President Trump was not involved.

To imply otherwise, while knowing the facts, is to weaponize this investigation as a smear campaign. I do not agree with that in any respect and will not allow this process to be used for such a purpose.

Chairman Comer and Oversight members will continue to provide updates and information as this investigation moves forward.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1836, Sam Houston was elected president of the Republic of Texas, which had recently gained independence from Mexico. 

Houston, who served in the War of 1812 and held political positions in Tennessee, played a crucial role in Texas' independence. He led a decisive victory at the Battle of San Jacinto, and was instrumental in Texas joining the United States in 1845. He served as a senator and governor, though he was later removed for opposing secession.

In a notable incident, Ohio Congressman William Stanbery accused Houston of fraud in a House speech. Two weeks later, Houston confronted Stanbery on Pennsylvania Avenue, calling him a "rascal" and attacking him with a hickory cane from his mentor‚Äôs, President Andrew Jackson‚Äôs, estate. Stanbery's attempt to defend himself with a pistol failed when it jammed. Houston's assault left Stanbery injured on the street. Houston was found in contempt by Congress and ordered to pay a $500 fine, which he never paid. Jackson later intervened to prevent the fine's collection.

The government‚Äôs failures on Social Security is a separate debate, but Social Security is FOR AMERICANS and Americans deserve every penny.

Foreign countries do not deserve American‚Äôs hard earned tax dollars and anyone demanding they do should register under FARA.

This 2022 estimate of the government‚Äôs spending of $8 TRILLION American tax dollars on foreign wars since 9/11, doesn‚Äôt include the hundreds of billions for Ukraine, however that $8 TRILLION spent was America LAST and unnecessarily drove America‚Äôs national debt.

The reality is Americans have been chained in over $37 TRILLION in debt and Americans deserve their Social Security money they were FORCED to pay!

The nuclear armed secular government of Israel is such a successful country that they have less than $400 billion in national debt and provide government funded healthcare and education to their citizens. 

Daily, Israel is proving that on their own, they are more than capable of destroying their enemies with no one‚Äôs help, as they not only destroy their enemies, they also destroy innocent lives.

Saying stop giving Israel $3.8 billion dollars a year isn‚Äôt Jew hatred or antisemitism, it‚Äôs just as simple as saying America can‚Äôt afford it anymore and shouldn‚Äôt have to continue paying.

Instead, defending continued funding of Israel over American‚Äôs own rights to Social Security is Israel First and America Last.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today at Laredo City Hall, I had the honor of presenting Bishop James A. Tamayo with a Congressional Record in recognition of his lifetime of service. Mayor Victor Trevi√±o also presented him with the Key to the City.
¬†
Bishop Tamayo‚Äôs life has been a blessing to our city, South Texas, and our country. Born in Brownsville, he answered the call to faith nearly fifty years ago and since then he has given everything he has to the Church, to our communities, and to the nation he served as a chaplain in the U.S. Air Force Reserve.
¬†
When Laredo became a diocese in 2000, Bishop Tamayo became its first bishop, building not just churches but bridges between cultures, families, and neighbors. His leadership has been defined by grace and love, a voice for the voiceless and a steady hand for those in need.
¬†
Today, we honor him not just for what he has done, but for who he is: a servant-leader and a light in our community.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1901, President William McKinley was shot twice while shaking hands with the public in New York. 

Although wounded, McKinley stayed conscious and said to ‚Äúbe careful how you tell my wife‚Äù and asked his guards not to harm his attacker. Doctors found that one bullet had grazed his sternum and another had penetrated his abdomen. 

Despite initial signs of recovery, McKinley‚Äôs condition deteriorated due to gangrene, leading to his death several days later. Vice President Theodore Roosevelt was sworn in as president.

Before McKinley‚Äôs assassination, the Secret Service's role primarily involved investigating counterfeit currency and did not include full-time presidential protection.

In response, Congress assigned the Secret Service the permanent duty of protecting the president, a role it continues to fulfill today.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
Kean, Thomas H.
text:
I applaud President Trump for taking decisive action yesterday to create a designation for state sponsors of wrongful detention of Americans. In June, I joined @RepFrenchHill (AR-02), @RepMikeLawler (NY-17), @RepJoshG (NJ-05), and @RepMoskowitz (FL-23) in introducing the bipartisan Countering Wrongful Detention Act of 2025, which establishes this very designation for countries or nonstate actors that hold American citizens or permanent residents hostage. This legislation equips both the Secretary of State and Congress with¬†new tools to hold these governments accountable by encouraging a range of penalties.
¬†
For my constituent, Sarah (Levinson) Moriarty, this issue hits especially close to home. Her father, Robert Levinson, was taken hostage by Iran in 2007. For years, her family lived in absolute uncertainty, wondering where he was, whether he was alive, or if they would ever see him again. Unfortunately, they never did. Far too many American families have endured that same fear, heartbreak, and loss. With this important legislation, paired with today‚Äôs executive order, we are making real strides to ensure that no family is ever forced to live through this tragedy again.
¬†
Hostile regimes like Iran continue to use innocent Americans as bargaining chips by dehumanizing, abusing, and in some cases killing them. This legislation would codify President Trump‚Äôs executive order and make clear that there will be consequences for using Americans as political pawns. The United States will not tolerate this behavior, and we will always stand up for our citizens, no matter where they are in the world.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
If #Churchill were faced with the threat posed to #Chicago by @POTUS he may have said:

More than half of a year has passed since this struggle entered its fiercest phase. What a cataract of calamity has descended upon us since then. The trust of the people in Washington and Los Angeles suppressed; their voices silenced beneath bluster; their free institutions mocked. Our allies in truth and democracy harried and betrayed. Entire communities of our nation, gutted and abandoned, their hopes of fraternity as brutally torn as any rampart in war.
Yet here in Chicago, we stand‚Äîundaunted, unbroken, resolute. 

If in January, one had told us that, after such disaster and shock, we should stand upright in September, masters of our own resolve, firm in the conviction of ultimate triumph, few would have credited it. Yet so it is. Where others faltered, Chicago has not wavered. We are stronger today‚Äîstronger in spirit, stronger in unity, stronger in the faith that justice shall prevail‚Äîthan ever we have been before.

The Trump faction believed that the air of confusion, the tempest of words, could cow us‚Äîthat by unbridled assault upon truth, they could drive us to submission. Yet the good men and women of Chicago have risen nobly, as never before. They have labored unceasingly, they have restored their strength, they have bristled their city against tyranny from within or from without. Chicago today is a fortress for Democrat, a beacon of hope, a sentinel of justice.

It is quite plain that Mr. Trump could not admit defeat in his assault upon the institutions of American democracy without sustaining the most serious injury. If, after all his vainglorious boastings, his dire threats, and the lurid accounts so loudly trumpeted across the nation of the triumphs he claims to have inflicted‚Äîof the vast numbers of crimes he alleges were committed, of the multitudes he insists have risen to his cause, and of the pitiful weakness of our civic order‚Äîif, after all these extravagant tales of Washington and Los Angeles laid low, their citizens panic-stricken and despairing of their government, if, after such a torrent of words, his whole offensive should, in the end, be forced to dwindle and fade into nothingness, the gentleman‚Äôs reputation for veracity, slender though it already is, would suffer the most grievous discredit. 

We may be sure, therefore, that he will persist as long as strength and circumstance allow, and as long as the manifold preoccupations of his legal entanglements with Epstein are in need of diversion from public purview and discourse.

On the other hand, the Patriotic spirit of free men and women has increased in vigour. Our capacity for endurance is already shown to exceed theirs. Each falsehood, once unmasked, becomes a weapon against him. Each scheme revealed serves not his cause, but ours.

And so I say this: The gratitude of every home in Chicago, of every family that lifts its head in freedom, of every heart across this nation that esteems liberty above servitude, goes forth to those few champions of truth and courage, who against overwhelming odds, in the heat of this mighty trial, turn the tide by their devotion.

Never, in the field of public struggle, was so much owed by so many to so few.

Name: McClain Delaney, April
text:
Recently, I had the pleasure of sitting down with the Town of Lonaconing's Mayor Jack Coburn and other town officials for lunch. The homemade dip and chicken salad sandwiches were delicious, but what was most touching to me was the heart of service I found in each of those elected officials who showed up. 

We discussed the pressing infrastructure issues facing their residents, including the recently secured $986,000 of federal funds requested in May, which was approved to repair a central waterline in Lonaconing (I later visited the repair of that line and the neighbor who was impacted). While our office is still fighting for FEMA funding for flood damage across the county, I know that resources will continue to be needed from multiple avenues.

But what was most meaningful to me is that our luncheon and recent conversations demonstrate what government should look like: different stakeholders coming together to address our community‚Äôs problems. Every American should have access to clean water, community resources and the infrastructure needed to thrive, and our office is working to deliver those things in @AlleganyCoMD - Maryland and across Mountain Maryland. ~A

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Remember Tim Kaine, Hillary‚Äôs 2016 running mate who‚Äôs still a U.S. Senator? Yeah, neither does America.

But he resurfaced this week to suggest your rights come from government, not God.

Let‚Äôs take a look back in history and walk through how that idea has fueled tyrannies, and why America was built to reject it. üßµ

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: When someone says rights come from government, they‚Äôre not simply making a bad argument; they‚Äôre going even further, embracing a worldview that‚Äôs been used to justify authoritarianism.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Let‚Äôs start here: 

‚ÄúAll men are created equal‚Ä¶ endowed by their Creator with certain unalienable Rights‚Ä¶‚Äù 

That‚Äôs straight from the Declaration of Independence.

 Our rights don‚Äôt come from government. Government exists to protect them.

That‚Äôs the American idea.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Nazi Germany.

The Weimar Constitution promised rights, but Hitler rewrote them overnight.

Jews and political enemies lost every ‚Äúright‚Äù they had.

Why?

Because those rights came from the state.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
1790s France.

The Revolution tossed out God, declared rights came from the state, and claimed to act on behalf of ‚Äúreason.‚Äù

The result?

Mass executions and show trials. It was known as The Reign of Terror.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Mao‚Äôs China.

Mao mocked the idea of God-given rights. The Communist Party was the only authority.

If you disagreed with the regime, you disappeared.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Soviet Union.

Stalin‚Äôs constitution ‚Äúguaranteed‚Äù rights, as long as they aligned with Party doctrine.

Freedom of speech?

Only if you agreed with the government.

Millions were sent to the gulags.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
See the trend?

Every regime that claimed to grant rights also believed it had the power to revoke them.

They all had one thing in common:
Government as god.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Now contrast that with America:

Our founders were explicit in declaring that rights come from God, government‚Äôs job is to secure them ‚Äî not to define them, not to distribute them, and certainly not to take them.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
So when Tim Kaine says your rights come from government, he‚Äôs echoing ideas that have crushed freedom around the world and defying the very principles America was built on.

If someone thinks they give you your rights‚Ä¶
They also believe they can take them away.

Today I‚Äôm honored to join friends and family to celebrate the reopening of the McCormick Center at @bloomsburgu. What stands out isn‚Äôt the meals ‚Äì or even the soft-serve ice cream he and I loved ‚Äì but the way my parents greeted everyone we passed ‚Äì students, professors, staff ‚Äì with a warm hello and genuine conversation.
¬†
Looking back, I see how deeply my parents cared about this university ‚Äì the quality of the education and creating an environment where students could learn and realize their dreams. They poured themselves into the job and they recognized the power education had to shape our country‚Äôs future.
¬†
Their legacy of mentoring, educating, and serving others continues to inspire me through my career, and it‚Äôs a reminder of the difference we can all make.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.

This week will mark twenty-four years since our nation experienced the horrors of 9/11. Out of that devastating tragedy came a responsibility to act. 

Working alongside the indomitable Ellen Saracini, I authored the Saracini Aviation Safety Act, signed into law in 2018, to require secondary cockpit barriers on all new commercial aircraft, and the Saracini Enhanced Aviation Safety Act, signed into law last year, to retrofit the entire fleet.

These laws, named in honor of Ellen‚Äôs husband, Captain Victor Saracini of Bucks County, whom we lost on 9/11, are the direct result of years of her tireless advocacy and our work together to turn grief into action and safeguard the future.

We will not stop until every cockpit, on every aircraft, has the protections needed to keep our skies safe and ensure the horrors of 9/11 are never able to happen again.

Name: Keating, William R.
text:
Today I met Belarusian political activist Siarhei Tsikhanouski. My full statement:

Today, I met with @tsikhanouski_s - just three months after his release from political imprisonment in Belarus. This is a man who just 100 days ago was living in complete solitary confinement, in horrific conditions, after being illegally detained.¬† His bravery and resilience should be an example to us all.

As Belarus Caucus Co-Chair, I have worked for more than 5 years to help facilitate the release of Siarhei and the more than 1,300 political prisoners who remain behind bars. Siarhei is an example of courage, conviction, determination, and more than anything else ‚Äì love of his homeland.¬† He has consistently stood up in defense of the values he and the entire Free Belarus movement support. I know we have Siarhei‚Äôs support as we continue to advocate for those who remain behind bars.

While Siarhei was imprisoned, his wife, Sviatlana, advocated on his behalf and on behalf of all Belarusians who detest the brutal Lukashenka regime. In March 2020, as Chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Sviatlana testified before the Subcommittee in her first public interaction with the United States government. Then, and now, she continues the fight for a Free Belarus. I am so grateful that Siarhei has now rejoined her on this journey.

Today in the @FinancialCmte  Institutions Subcommittee, I underscored bipartisan support for giving community banks more flexibility to serve their customers.

The Community Bank Leverage Ratio‚Äî advanced under the First Trump Administration‚Äîset a simple 9% capital standard that reduced compliance costs and freed up resources for local lending for only the smallest banks. All witnesses agreed that lowering it further would expand access to credit and strengthen competition.

We also discussed the expansion of reciprocal deposits, a commonsense reform that provides customers with greater FDIC insurance protection without adding risk.

These are bipartisan solutions that strengthen community banks, support small businesses, and keep local economies growing.
